This project funded by the Dutch Relief Alliance aims to address gaps in education and protection in Masisi territory, North Kivu. War Child UK’s multi-sectoral package of activities under the Consortium headed by War Child Holland includes teacher’s training; catch-up classes; prevention and response to violence, exploitation, abuse and neglect in communities; referral mechanisms; child-friendly spaces; psychosocial support through War Child’s DEALs methodology; SGBV interventions through prevention and response; capacity-building of community-based protection structures; support to separated and unaccompanied children through care systems (foster families and family reunification); and increasing community awareness and capacity on children’s rights and child protection issues.

(1) With the helpline, children will be provided with advice from trained \\\"listeners\\\" (social workers, members of child parliament). State agents (DIVAS, police, CT, etc.) will have their capacities strengthened through training and provision of equipments. 
(2) Prevention and sensitisation activities will be undertaken through multi-media campaigns. A participative research activity will be undertaken through multimedia campaigns.;

An integrated FSL and CP Project will be implemented in Bani Husaish, Sanaa Governorate to assist children and families affected by COVID-19, including IDPs who are among the most vulnerable groups in the context of the pandemic. WCUK will assist 488 new IDPs Households (HHs) through provision of unconditional cash assistance covering the Minimum Food Basket (MFB) and will further provide cash for protection assistance to 112 identified vulnerable cases. Finally, WCUK will provide legal documentation support to IDPs communities. Due to the conflict in Yemen and the crisis most of the IDPs do not have legal documents, as they either lost them or left them behind in their houses. Children need birth certificates to be able to join schools and get further help from other organizations. Parents need IDs as well to be able to receive any type of help such as cash and food baskets, etc. WC UK will assist IDPs without documentation and referring them to appropriate authorities. These documents will include issuing birth certificates for children and IDs for adults (+18).
A small top-up received from the Leri Charitable Trust to be spent on supporting the VoiceMore assistant under PACE/AidConnect in the DRC, whose salary costs are not fully covered by the grant.
